Below is a **single, production‑grade `README.md`** you can drop into your repo root.\
It’s written so that **you (future‑you in a year) or any new engineer** can clone the repo, understand the architecture, run it safely, and extend it with confidence.

***

# Terraform AWS Infra + CI (Plan · Security · Cost · Artifacts)

> A opinionated Terraform project that provisions a minimal AWS stack (VPC → Security Group → EC2) and validates it in **GitHub Actions** with **fmt/validate/TFLint**, **tfsec**, **Checkov**, a binary **plan** + **JSON/text** exports, and **Infracost** cost estimates—**all uploaded as artifacts** per run.

**Highlights**

*   **State**: S3 backend with **Versioning** & **Encryption** (must exist before `terraform init`). [\[docs.github.com\]](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/secure-your-work/security-harden-deployments/oidc-in-aws)
*   **Auth**: GitHub → AWS via **OIDC** (short‑lived credentials—no access keys).
*   **Plan JSON**: `terraform show -json` exported from the **same working directory** as `init/plan` so provider schemas are available. [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/hashicorp/setup-terraform), [\[youtube.com\]](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pa5nDPvk30M)
*   **Security**: **Checkov** (soft‑fail, SARIF) & **tfsec** (SARIF) hooked to GitHub code scanning patterns. [\[cli.github.com\]](https://cli.github.com/), [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/cli/cli/blob/trunk/docs/install_linux.md), [\[cicube.io\]](https://cicube.io/workflow-hub/hashicorp-setup-terraform/)
*   **Artifacts**: Uploaded with **Artifacts v4** (faster, immutable). [\[docs.datadoghq.com\]](https://docs.datadoghq.com/security/code_security/iac_security/iac_rules/terraform/aws/ec2_not_ebs_optimized/), [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/terraform-linters/tflint-ruleset-terraform/blob/main/docs/rules/terraform_required_providers.md)

## 1. Repository Map

    .
    ├─ README.md                     # ← this file
    ├─ .github/
    │  └─ workflows/
    │     └─ terraform-ci.yml        # CI: plan + security + cost + artifacts
    └─ terraform-project/
       ├─ backend.tf                 # S3 backend (bucket/key/region, optional lockfile)
       ├─ main.tf                    # root wires VPC + SG + EC2 modules
       ├─ variables.tf               # all inputs for the root module
       ├─ outputs.tf                 # root outputs
       ├─ *.auto.tfvars              # (optional) environment defaults
       └─ modules/
          ├─ vpc/                    # VPC, subnets, (optionally flow logs)
          ├─ security-group/         # SG with SSH restricted to admin CIDR; egress scoped
          └─ ec2/                    # EC2 with EBS encryption, monitoring, IAM instance profile

> *Note*: The CI runs **inside** `./terraform-project` so the provider plugins that `init` installs are available when we export **plan JSON**. Running `show -json` elsewhere often causes the vendor schema error; keep it here. [\[youtube.com\]](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pa5nDPvk30M)

## 3. What We Provision (Infra Overview)

*   **VPC** with private subnets (optionally enable flow logs in your module if desired).
*   **Security Group** with:
    *   `ingress`: **SSH from admin CIDR only**, never `0.0.0.0/0`.
    *   `egress`: **constrained** (e.g., to VPC CIDR).
*   **EC2 instance** with:
    *   EBS optimization & **detailed monitoring** enabled.
    *   Root EBS **encrypted** (optionally via KMS CMK; otherwise AWS‑managed).
    *   **IAM instance profile** attached (e.g., SSM core) so we can use Session Manager instead of public SSH.
*   **S3 remote state**:
    *   Bucket **pre‑created**; Terraform will **not** create it at `init`.
    *   **Versioning** and **encryption** enabled (recommended by HashiCorp). [\[docs.github.com\]](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/secure-your-work/security-harden-deployments/oidc-in-aws)

## 4. One‑Time Bootstrap

### 4.1 Create the S3 backend bucket

**Console (recommended for first‑timers)**\
S3 → *Create bucket* → Name `tfstate-brajesh-prod` (or your naming), Region `us-east-1`, *Block public access: ON*, *Versioning: Enable*, *Default encryption: SSE‑S3 (AES‑256)*.\
Terraform’s S3 backend expects the bucket to exist before `init`. Versioning is recommended for safe recovery. [\[docs.github.com\]](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/secure-your-work/security-harden-deployments/oidc-in-aws)

**CLI (idempotent snippet)**

```bash
BUCKET="tfstate-brajesh-prod"
REGION="us-east-1"

if aws s3api head-bucket --bucket "$BUCKET" 2>/dev/null; then
  echo "Bucket exists"
else
  if [ "$REGION" = "us-east-1" ]; then
    aws s3api create-bucket --bucket "$BUCKET" --region "$REGION"
  else
    aws s3api create-bucket --bucket "$BUCKET" --region "$REGION" \
      --create-bucket-configuration LocationConstraint="$REGION"
  fi
  aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket "$BUCKET" \
    --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled
  aws s3api put-bucket-encryption --bucket "$BUCKET" \
    --server-side-encryption-configuration \
    '{"Rules":[{"ApplyServerSideEncryptionByDefault":{"SSEAlgorithm":"AES256"}}]}'
fi
```

**`backend.tf` (root)**

```hcl
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket       = "tfstate-brajesh-prod"
    key          = "envs/prod/terraform.tfstate"
    region       = "us-east-1"
    # use_lockfile = true  # native S3 locking; DynamoDB lock is being deprecated
  }
}
```

> The S3 backend page documents that **DynamoDB‑based locking is deprecated** and S3 lockfile is available; keep that in mind if you migrate older stacks. [\[docs.github.com\]](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/secure-your-work/security-harden-deployments/oidc-in-aws)

### 4.2 Configure GitHub OIDC → AWS

Create a GitHub OIDC IdP and a role that your repo/branch can assume, then add to the workflow:

```yaml
- name: Configure AWS credentials (OIDC)
  uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
  with:
    role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::<ACCOUNT_ID>:role/<GITHUB_OIDC_ROLE>
    aws-region: us-east-1
```

*   The action injects short‑lived AWS credentials into env vars for subsequent steps.
*   The AWS Security blog shows end‑to‑end setup with console & CLI.

## 5. Local Development

From **`./terraform-project`**:

```bash
terraform init
terraform plan -out=plan.tfplan
terraform show -json plan.tfplan > plan.json
terraform show plan.tfplan > plan.txt
```

> Run `show -json` in the same directory used for `init/plan`, so Terraform can load provider **schemas** and render the plan JSON. [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/hashicorp/setup-terraform), [\[youtube.com\]](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pa5nDPvk30M)

***

## 6. CI/CD Pipeline (GitHub Actions)

**File**: `.github/workflows/terraform-ci.yml`

### 6.1 What it does

1.  **Checkout** → **OIDC assume role** to AWS.
2.  `terraform fmt -check` and `terraform validate` (non‑blocking for early adoption).
3.  **TFLint** for style/idioms.
4.  **tfsec** publishes **SARIF** + text so you can wire into GitHub code scanning. [\[cicube.io\]](https://cicube.io/workflow-hub/hashicorp-setup-terraform/)
5.  **Checkov** runs with `soft_fail: true` so you get findings without failing the job; emits SARIF + text. [\[cli.github.com\]](https://cli.github.com/), [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/cli/cli/blob/trunk/docs/install_linux.md)
6.  `terraform plan -out=plan.tfplan` (binary).
7.  `terraform show -json` and `show` export **JSON** and **text** to `reports/` (must run in module dir). [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/hashicorp/setup-terraform)
8.  **Infracost** breakdown → `reports/infracost-breakdown.json/.txt` (action v3).
9.  **Artifacts v4** uploads `plan.tfplan` + `reports/*` (fast, immutable). [\[docs.datadoghq.com\]](https://docs.datadoghq.com/security/code_security/iac_security/iac_rules/terraform/aws/ec2_not_ebs_optimized/), [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/terraform-linters/tflint-ruleset-terraform/blob/main/docs/rules/terraform_required_providers.md)

### 6.2 Minimal snippet (excerpt)

```yaml
- name: Terraform plan (binary)
  working-directory: ./terraform-project
  run: terraform plan -out=plan.tfplan -no-color

- name: Export plan to JSON & text
  working-directory: ./terraform-project
  run: |
    terraform show -json plan.tfplan > ../reports/plan.json
    terraform show -no-color plan.tfplan > ../reports/plan.txt
```

## 7. Inputs, Defaults & Conventions

*   **Set defaults** in `variables.tf` for friction‑free CI. Example:

```hcl
variable "ami_id"        { type = string, default = "ami-0c02fb55956c7d316" } # us-east-1 AL2
variable "instance_type" { type = string, default = "t3.micro" }
variable "environment"   { type = string, default = "prod" }
variable "vpc_cidr"      { type = string, default = "10.0.0.0/16" }
variable "admin_cidr"    { type = string, default = "203.0.113.0/24" }
```

*   Alternatively, commit `*.auto.tfvars` in `./terraform-project` or inject `TF_VAR_*` in CI env.
*   Root module wires:
    *   `module.vpc` → outputs `vpc_id`, `private_subnet_ids`.
    *   `module.security_group` → outputs `security_group_id`.
    *   `module.ec2` gets `subnet_id` and `security_group_id` from those outputs.

## 8. Artifacts: What You Get After Each Run

**Actions → select run → Artifacts → `terraform-plan-and-reports` (zip)** contains:

    plan.tfplan
    reports/
      plan.json
      plan.txt
      terraform_validate.txt
      tflint.txt
      tfsec.sarif
      tfsec.txt
      checkov.sarif
      checkov.txt
      terraform_fmt.diff (if enabled)
      infracost-breakdown.json
      infracost-breakdown.txt

Artifacts are uploaded via **actions/upload-artifact\@v4** (faster & reliable). [\[docs.datadoghq.com\]](https://docs.datadoghq.com/security/code_security/iac_security/iac_rules/terraform/aws/ec2_not_ebs_optimized/), [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/terraform-linters/tflint-ruleset-terraform/blob/main/docs/rules/terraform_required_providers.md)

## 9. Troubleshooting & Runbook

### 9.1 `terraform init` → “S3 bucket does not exist”

Create the bucket first. Terraform S3 backend **expects a pre‑existing bucket** and recommends **Versioning**. Wait a few seconds after creation, then re‑run. [\[docs.github.com\]](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/secure-your-work/security-harden-deployments/oidc-in-aws), [\[cloudquery.io\]](https://www.cloudquery.io/blog/keyless-access-to-aws-in-github-actions-with-oidc)

### 9.2 `terraform show -json` → “Failed to load plugin schemas”

Run `show` from the **same dir** where `init/plan` ran (so local provider binaries & schemas can be loaded). [\[youtube.com\]](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pa5nDPvk30M)

### 9.3 CI can’t assume AWS role

Check that your workflow has `permissions: id-token: write` and your IAM role trust policy matches your repo/branch; use the **official** OIDC action.

### 9.4 Checkov fails the build (you want learning, not blocking)

Set `soft_fail: true` (already configured here). You’ll still get CLI/SARIF outputs for code scanning. [\[cli.github.com\]](https://cli.github.com/)
